First, the volume of the prepared eggshell@CQDs was studied using five levels: 50,100,150,200, and 250 µL. Each of these volumes was added to a set volume of molnupiravir stock solution to get a concentration of 20 µg/mL and the volume was completed to 10 mL with deionized water in a 10 mL volumetric flask. It was found that the highest fluorescence quenching was obtained using 200 µL of the prepared eggshell@CQDs (
                              Fig. S6
                           ) which was subsequently used in further optimization.

The pH of the solution is widely known to alter not only the fluorescence intensity of CQDs but also the interactions between the CQDs and the quencher [40]. To investigate the effect of pH on the reaction between the prepared eggshell@CQDs and molnupiravir, several pH values were adjusted using a universal Britton-Robinson buffer (0.05 M) from 2 to 10 [41]. The effect of pH was checked in the absence and presence of molnupiravir, and F°/F was calculated. It was noted that changing pH using the buffer reduces the quenching effect of molnupiravir and the highest quenching was obtained in the absence of pH adjustment (
                              Fig. S7
                           ). As a result, no pH adjustment was required in subsequent procedures, and the method was conducted using deionized water, which adds benefit to the developed method.

Because of its significant effect on the quenching process, the incubation time was examined. Fluorescence spectra were recorded after molnupiravir was added to eggshell@CQDs. At different time intervals in the range from 0 to 20 min, the efficiency of fluorescence quenching in the presence of molnupiravir was determined. The maximum fluorescence quenching was obtained in 1 min, and no further quenching was seen as the reaction time was extended. Another benefit of this approach is that the reaction between molnupiravir and eggshell@CQDs was found to be quick, taking around a minute to complete, and the fluorescence emission was stable for over 20 min (
                              Fig. S8
                           ).

The selectivity of the method was examined by checking the effect of several antiviral and antibacterial agents on the fluorescence intensity of the prepared eggshell@CQDs. It was noticed that molnupiravir had a remarkable quenching impact on the fluorescence of eggshell@CQDs compared to other agents (
                           Fig. S9
                        ). To verify the excipient interference, molnupiravir was checked with a variety of excipients, including, HPMC, CMC, sorbitol, mannitol, glucose, sucrose, fructose, magnesium stearate, and lactose. The outcomes demonstrate that the excipients had no influence, suggesting that the designed method has a high selectivity (
                           Fig. S10
                        ).

Although many principles have been presented for evaluating green practices in analytical procedures, the use of the Eco-scale, GAPI, and AGREE together were recommended for a comprehensive evaluation of an analytical method that provides collaborative results. The new spectrofluorometric approach was examined with the previously listed tools and compared to the described HPLC method. The eco-scale score was determined, which took into account the amount of solvents used and offered further information about the ecological effects of the method [47]. The suggested method achieved a score of 93 (
                           Table S3
                        ) demonstrating a good green approach of analysis with minimum harmful impact on the environment and human well-being. GAPI provided a comprehensive overview of several aspects of the analysis steps such as preparation of the sample, handling of the sample (collection, preservation, transfer, and storage), chemicals utilized, and instruments. Each element was coloured in a range of colours, from green to yellow to red, to indicate a low, medium, or high impact on the environment. The developed method has a majority of green sectors and the fewest red ones (9 green and 3 red). In contrast, the HPLC method appeared to be less green (5 green and 4 red). Lastly, the AGREE software was employed, which presented the greenness profile as a value in numerical form, (0.74) for the spectrofluorometric technique and (0.52) for the HPLC one, demonstrating the upper hand of the proposed approach in terms of greenness (Fig. 5
                        ). Overall, the outputs from all the tools used for assessment offered an extensive greenness description, strengthened each other, and, for the most part, verified the implementation of green practices.

Although many principles have been proposed for evaluating green practices in analytical procedures, it is suggested to utilize the Eco-scale, GAPI, and AGREE together to comprehensively evaluate an analytical method and obtain collaborative results. In the case of the new spectrofluorometric approach, it was evaluated using the aforementioned tools and compared to the described HPLC method. The eco-scale score was determined to assess the ecological effects of the method, taking into account the amount of solvents used. The suggested method achieved a score of 93 (
                           Table S3
                        ), indicating a good green approach with minimal harmful impact on the environment and human well-being. GAPI provided a comprehensive overview of different aspects of the analysis steps, such as sample preparation, sample handling, chemicals used, and instruments employed. Each element was assigned a colour, ranging from green to yellow to red, indicating a low, medium, or high environmental impact. The developed method had mostly green sectors and the fewest red ones (9 green and 3 red), while the HPLC method appeared to be less green (5 green and 4 red). Additionally, the AGREE software was utilized, which presented the greenness profile as a numerical value. The spectrofluorometric technique obtained a greenness value of 0.74, while the HPLC method scored 0.52, highlighting the superiority of the proposed approach in terms of greenness (Fig. 5). Overall, the outcomes from all the assessment tools provided a comprehensive description of the greenness of the methods, corroborating the implementation of green practices in the spectrofluorometric approach.
